item.title: 'Surgery was painful': UnitedHealthcare CEO killer Luigi Mangione's social media posts indicate about his health struggles
item.description: Luigi Mangione, suspected in the killing of UnitedHealthcare CEO Brian Thompson, openly documented his journey with chronic back pain and spinal surgery on social media. His posts initially reflected relief after a successful operation in 2023.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'Heart of Jupiter moon Io's rage': Nasa captures active volcano erupting into space
item.description: NASA's Juno mission revealed that Jupiter's moon, Io, the most volcanic body in our solar system, doesn't possess a global magma ocean. Instead, separate magma chambers fuel its over 400 active volcanoes, solving a 44-year-old mystery. Juno's gravity data, collected during recent flybys, confirms this, impacting our understanding of other moons and exoplanets.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Five minutes to martial law: South Korea's Yoon stunned cabinet with snap move
item.description: South Korean President Yoon Suk Yeol's sudden declaration of martial law on December 3rd plunged the nation into chaos. A late-night cabinet meeting, convened with little notice, revealed Yoon's unilateral decision, sparking fierce objections from ministers concerned about economic fallout. Despite pleas, Yoon proceeded with the declaration, triggering market panic and a dramatic parliamentary response.

item.title: Canadian premiers urge Trudeau to take strong action against looming US tariffs
item.description: Canadian premiers urged Prime Minister Trudeau to strongly counter US President-elect Trump's threatened tariffs. They proposed retaliatory measures, including halting energy exports, citing US reliance on Canadian goods. Trump's tariffs, expected soon after his inauguration, are conditional on addressing drug and immigration concerns. The US imported hundreds of billions of dollars worth of goods from Canada in recent years.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: No evidence to suggest mysterious New Jersey drones work of foreign adversary: White House
item.description: Mysterious drones have been buzzing over New Jersey, sparking UFO theories and concerns. The Pentagon denies any foreign involvement, specifically dismissing Rep. Jeff Van Drew's suggestion of an Iranian "mothership." However, the FBI admits uncertainty, even suggesting some sightings might be misidentified aircraft.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Did 'life-altering injury' drive Luigi Mangione to kill UnitedHealthcare CEO? Cops share new details
item.description: Police arrested Luigi Mangione, 26, in Pennsylvania for the murder of UnitedHealthcare CEO Brian Thompson in NYC. Mangione's July back injury and subsequent surgery are suspected motives. A note criticizing the US healthcare system and a notebook detailing the murder plan were found with Mangione. He is fighting extradition to New York.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Who is Travis Timmerman? US man found in Syria after spending months in prison
item.description: Travis Timmerman, a US citizen, has been freed after months of detention in a Syrian prison following the Assad regime's overthrow. He was found on Thursday and recounted his experience to CBS News, detailing his unauthorized entry into Syria and subsequent capture. Timmerman is now seeking to leave Syria, and the US government is working to bring him home.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Denmark jails Sanjay Shah, a hedge fund trader, for tax fraud
US court charges former Syrian prison head Samir Ousman Alsheikh with torture
item.description: Samir Alsheikh, a former Syrian prison head, was charged in the US with torturing political prisoners during his tenure at Adra Prison. He allegedly oversaw brutal practices and later lied on immigration applications. Alsheikh faces potential decades-long prison sentences if convicted of torture and immigration fraud.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Troops to stay in Syria buffer zone for now: Israel
item.description: Following the collapse of the Assad regime, Israeli forces have secured Syrian territory, establishing a defensive perimeter. Prime Minister Netanyahu stated the occupation is temporary, citing the need to prevent jihadist groups from threatening Israeli communities. The move has drawn international concern, with France urging Israel to respect Syria's sovereignty and withdraw.

item.title: Amazon to contribute $1 million to Trump’s inauguration, founder Bezos seeks stronger ties with President-elect
item.description: Amazon is poised to donate $1 million to Trump's inauguration, following a similar contribution from Meta. Both Bezos and Zuckerberg have met with Trump, signaling a thaw in relations after past criticisms and controversies. Bezos recently defended The Washington Post's decision to abstain from a 2024 presidential endorsement amid internal backlash.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Mujib's 'Joy Bangla' no longer national slogan
item.description: Bangladesh's Supreme Court suspended a High Court ruling that declared 'Joy Bangla' the national slogan. The interim government, led by Muhammad Yunus, challenged the March 2020 verdict after Sheikh Hasina's ouster. The court stated the slogan is a policy matter outside judicial purview.

item.title: Suspect in Brian Thompson's murder Luigi Mangione not a client of UnitedHealthcare, says police
item.description: Luigi Mangione, suspected of killing UnitedHealthcare CEO Brian Thompson, was arrested in Pennsylvania. Police believe Mangione targeted Thompson due to UnitedHealthcare's size and influence, not a personal connection. Mangione, found with a "ghost gun," awaits extradition to New York on murder charges while resisting extradition. He faces additional charges in Pennsylvania.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'Distress, hurt, and harm': US President-elect Trump joins union fight, criticises automation's impact on dockworkers
item.description: President-elect Trump voiced support for 45,000 dockworkers locked in a labor dispute over automation. He argued that the cost savings from automation don't justify the job losses. Trump urged foreign shipping companies benefiting from US markets to prioritize American workers over machinery, especially given their record profits.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 97-year-old judge takes legal action against suspension over mental fitness
item.description: 97-year-old Judge Pauline Newman is fighting her suspension from the Federal Circuit, denying claims of mental unfitness. She argues delays in her opinions were due to meticulousness, not cognitive decline, and claims colleagues threatened her for seeking transparency. Her legal team, the NCLA, calls the suspension unconstitutional, citing clean medical evaluations and lack of due process.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Four men to face trial over online harassment of France's first lady Brigitte Macron
item.description: Four individuals will face trial in Paris next year for online harassment of French First Lady Brigitte Macron. The charges relate to disinformation and malicious comments concerning her gender, sexuality, and age gap with President Emmanuel Macron. This follows a complaint filed by the First Lady in August, and the accused face potential prison sentences if convicted.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Trump wants ‘peace, not killing’ in Middle-East, says ‘I don’t trust anybody’
item.description: President-elect Trump aims to personally broker peace between Israel and Hamas, distrusting even Netanyahu. He prioritizes ending violence over specific solutions like a two-state solution or annexation, citing the October 7 attacks. Huckabee's ambassador appointment raises questions about settlement policy, while Trump expresses confidence in achieving Middle East peace despite past setbacks.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: FBI did not send undercover agents to join January 6 Capitol attack: Watchdog report
item.description: A Justice Department report debunks claims of FBI involvement in the January 6 Capitol attack. Investigators found no undercover agents or informants instigating violence, despite the presence of 26 FBI informants in D.C. that day. Though one informant entered the Capitol, none acted on FBI instructions.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: ‘Vanderpump Rules’ actor James Kennedy arrested for domestic violence: Report
item.description: Former "Vanderpump Rules" star James Kennedy was arrested Tuesday night in Burbank for alleged misdemeanor domestic violence. Police responded to a private residence after a witness reported Kennedy being physical with an unidentified woman. Kennedy was released on bail, and the case is under review. The incident followed a holiday party where Kennedy reportedly displayed erratic behavior.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: ‘We're going to have a big discussion’: Trump signals vaccine policy review with RFK Jr
item.description: President-elect Donald Trump is considering changes to childhood vaccination programs, citing concerns about autism rates. He plans to discuss the matter with HHS nominee Robert F. Kennedy Jr., a known vaccine skeptic. Kennedy's potential appointment raises concerns among health experts due to his controversial views contradicting scientific consensus on vaccine safety.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk
